#compdef netwatch
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# netwatch — real-time network diagnostics TUI: packet capture +
#            connection-level flow tracking + GeoIP-tagged remote
#            endpoints + TLS SNI / HTTP request line / QUIC Initial
#            decoding + flight recorder for incident replay, in a
#            ratatui dashboard with 7 tabs (Rust, 1916★)
#
# upstream: https://github.com/matthart1983/netwatch
# author : Matt Hartley (matthart1983)
# license: MIT
# crate  : `netwatch-tui` (provides single `netwatch` bin)
#
# Source-direct completion: every flag below is verbatim from src/main.rs
# on the matthart1983/netwatch tip — the manual argv-scan logic
# (`args.iter().any(|a| a == "--version")` etc) parsed exactly as
# declared, with the --remote/--api-key dependency relationship
# preserved.  netwatch uses ad-hoc flag parsing in main rather than a
# clap derive so the TUI can come up immediately when no flags are
# present (sudo netwatch with no args = full mode).  In-TUI keybindings
# (1-7 tab switch, / filter, q quit, Shift+R/F/E flight recorder
# arm/freeze/export) come from the embedded --help text.
#
# Direct deps from Cargo.toml (selected):
#   maxminddb               "0.27"   ← canonical Rust MaxMind DB / GeoIP
#                                       reader library (this axis) — by
#                                       Gregory Oschwald (oschwald/
#                                       maxminddb-rust); pure-Rust
#                                       reader for the MaxMind binary
#                                       database format used by every
#                                       commercial GeoIP product
#                                       (GeoIP2-City, GeoIP2-Country,
#                                       GeoIP2-ISP, GeoIP2-ASN) and
#                                       MaxMind's free GeoLite2-City /
#                                       GeoLite2-Country / GeoLite2-ASN
#                                       distributions.  Supports both
#                                       generic `Reader::lookup::<T>()`
#                                       with serde-deserialized record
#                                       types and the `City` / `Country`
#                                       / `Isp` / `Asn` predefined
#                                       record shapes shared with the
#                                       MaxMind format spec.  THE Rust
#                                       answer to "given this IP, what
#                                       country/city/ASN is it?" Used
#                                       by sniffnet, trippy, vector,
#                                       openobserve, quilkin (Embark's
#                                       UDP proxy), hayabusa
#                                       (Yamato-Security's threat
#                                       hunter), trailbase, and most
#                                       Rust networking/observability
#                                       tools that need IP geolocation.
#                                       netwatch uses it to enrich
#                                       captured packet headers'
#                                       source/dest IPs with country
#                                       flag + ASN/ISP tags in the
#                                       "Connections" + "Endpoints"
#                                       tabs of the TUI, so traffic
#                                       to a Cloudflare IP shows
#                                       "Cloudflare, Inc. (AS13335)"
#                                       inline.
#   ratatui                          (TUI framework — 7-tab dashboard)
#   crossterm                        (terminal manipulation +
#                                       EnterAlternateScreen /
#                                       EnableMouseCapture)
#   pcap                  "2"        (libpcap bindings for packet
#                                       capture — requires
#                                       `sudo netwatch` or
#                                       cap_net_raw on Linux)
#   tls-parser            "0.12"     (Suricata-folks rusticata TLS
#                                       ClientHello / SNI extraction)
#   httparse              "1.10"     (HTTP/1 request line parser)
#   ring                             (AEAD primitives for QUIC Initial
#                                       decryption — RFC 9001
#                                       HKDF-Expand-Label + AES-128-GCM
#                                       AEAD + AES-128-ECB header
#                                       protection via
#                                       `ring::aead::quic`)
#   tokio                            (async runtime for the capture
#                                       worker + render loop)
#   mimalloc                         (mimalloc replaces glibc ptmalloc /
#                                       system allocator — long-running
#                                       TUI daemons pay an RSS tax to
#                                       ptmalloc's per-thread arena
#                                       retention; mimalloc returns
#                                       memory to the OS more
#                                       aggressively)
#   chrono + serde + serde_json + toml + dirs + anyhow + ureq + uuid
#
# netwatch is a one-binary, zero-config replacement for the
# nload/iftop/netstat/wireshark-tshark stack — `sudo netwatch` (root
# required for raw socket / pcap access) brings up a 7-tab ratatui
# dashboard showing live bandwidth, per-connection flow stats,
# DPI-extracted protocol fields (TLS SNI, HTTP host headers, QUIC
# Initial packet contents), and a "flight recorder" mode that buffers
# the last N seconds of packet metadata for export to .cast/.json for
# post-incident replay.  GeoIP enrichment via maxminddb tags each
# remote IP with its country + ASN, surfaced inline in the
# Connections + Endpoints tabs.  Optional `--remote <url> --api-key
# <key>` streams the same metrics to a NetWatch Core instance for
# fleet aggregation.
#
# ============================================================================
# === AXIS 186 OPENS — MaxMind DB / GeoIP IP geolocation reader ============
# === Rust=241 OPENS at slot 1/0/0 ========================================
# ============================================================================
# Axis position: Rust=241 OPENS Axis 186 at slot 1/0/0 — the first of the
# three lanes for the canonical MaxMind DB / GeoIP reader trio.  The
# axis anchors on a single pure-host-language reader for the MaxMind
# binary database format (`.mmdb`) used by every commercial GeoIP
# product (GeoIP2-City / GeoIP2-Country / GeoIP2-ISP / GeoIP2-ASN /
# GeoIP2-Domain / GeoIP2-AnonymousIP) and MaxMind's free GeoLite2
# distributions:
#
#     Rust    : maxminddb                    by Gregory Oschwald
#                                              (oschwald/maxminddb-
#                                              rust); pure-Rust reader
#                                              with generic
#                                              `Reader::lookup::<T>()`
#                                              + serde-deserialized
#                                              record types + predefined
#                                              City / Country / Isp /
#                                              Asn record shapes shared
#                                              with the MaxMind format
#                                              spec.  Notable: Gregory
#                                              Oschwald ALSO maintains
#                                              the canonical Go reader
#                                              (`geoip2-golang`) — same
#                                              author across two
#                                              lanes, unusual on cross-
#                                              language axes.
#                 → netwatch (Matt Hartley matthart1983 — real-time
#                              network diagnostics TUI; 7-tab ratatui
#                              dashboard with pcap-based packet
#                              capture + TLS SNI / HTTP request /
#                              QUIC Initial DPI + GeoIP-tagged remote
#                              endpoints via maxminddb; flight recorder
#                              for incident replay; optional remote
#                              streaming to a NetWatch Core instance;
#                              1916★ MIT)
#                 _netwatch         [Rust=241 OPENS Axis 186, 1/0/0]
#                                                  ↑↑↑ THIS FILE ↑↑↑
#
#     Go      : (next round — Go=241, slot 2/0/0)
#                Canonical Go MaxMind DB reader: github.com/oschwald/
#                geoip2-golang by Gregory Oschwald (SAME AUTHOR as the
#                Rust crate) — same API shape, same record types, same
#                MaxMind format spec.  Used by Caddy's IP filter, Hugo's
#                page-level IP-based rendering hooks, Traefik's GeoIP
#                middleware, and most Go networking tools that need IP
#                geolocation.  [TBD next-round consumer]
#
#     JS/Node : (Axis 186 CLOSES at TS-Node=241, slot 1/1/1)
#                Canonical JS MaxMind DB reader: `maxmind` by Egor Runov
#                (runk/node-maxmind) — pure-JS reader for the same
#                .mmdb format, with the same record types as the Rust
#                and Go libraries.  No relation to Gregory Oschwald
#                (different maintainer) but the API mirrors the format
#                spec.  Used by hundreds of npm-ecosystem
#                observability/proxy tools.  [TBD closer consumer]
#
# Cycle position in current 3+1 micro-cycle:
#   Rust=241     ← THIS FILE          (axis 186 OPENS, slot 1/0/0)
#   Go=241       ← next round         (axis 186 continues, slot 2/0/0)
#   TS-Node=241  ← round after        (axis 186 CLOSES at triple-241, 1/1/1)
# ============================================================================

_netwatch() {
    _arguments -s -S \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help (with TUI keybindings reference)]' \
        '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[print version]' \
        '--generate-config[write a default config file (~/.config/netwatch/config.toml) and exit]' \
        '--remote=[stream metrics to a NetWatch Core instance at this URL (requires --api-key)]:url:' \
        '--api-key=[API key for the remote streaming target]:key:' \
        '--no-sandbox[disable the post-startup security sandbox (raw socket privileges retained for the entire process lifetime)]' \
        '--sandbox-strict[refuse to start if the security sandbox cannot be enforced on this platform]'
}

_netwatch "$@"
